pg?resize=1536,864 1536w\" width=\"396\" height=\"223\" loading=\"lazy\" data-original-width=\"396\" data-original-height=\"223\" itemprop=\"http://schema.org/image\" title=\"how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0002\" alt=\"MESFET\"/\u003e \u003c/a\u003e \u003cp\u003e MESFET \u003c/p\u003e \u003c/div\u003e  \u003cdiv itemprop=\"associatedMedia\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ImageObject\" data-original-width=\"400\" data-original-height=\"227\"\u003e \u003ca href=\"https://hackaday.com/2025/04/05/how-shrinking-feature-size-made-modern-wireless-work/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003/\" itemprop=\"url\"\u003e \u003cmeta itemprop=\"width\" content=\"396\"/\u003e \u003cmeta itemprop=\"height\" content=\"223\"/\u003e \u003cimg decoding=\"async\" data-attachment-id=\"770596\" data-orig-file=\"https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg\" data-orig-size=\"1920,1080\" data-comments-opened=\"1\" data-image-meta=\"{\u0026#34;aperture\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;0\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;credit\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;camera\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;caption\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;created_timestamp\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;0\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;copyright\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;focal_length\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;0\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;iso\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;0\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;shutter_speed\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;0\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;title\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;orientation\u0026#34;:\u0026#34;0\u0026#34;}\" data-image-title=\"how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003\" data-image-description=\"\" data-medium-file=\"https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg?w=400\" data-large-file=\"https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg?w=800\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg?w=396\u0026amp;h=223\u0026amp;ssl=1\" srcset=\"https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg 1920w, https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg?resize=250,141 250w, https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg?resize=400,225 400w, https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg?resize=800,450 800w, https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003.jpg?resize=1536,864 1536w\" width=\"396\" height=\"223\" loading=\"lazy\" data-original-width=\"396\" data-original-height=\"223\" itemprop=\"http://schema.org/image\" title=\"how-moores-law-revolutionized-rf-cmos-b2g23mwskmw-webm-shot0003\" alt=\"MOSFET\"/\u003e \u003c/a\u003e \u003cp\u003e MOSFET \u003c/p\u003e \u003c/div\u003e  \u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe basic overview is that in the 1960s, most high-frequency stuff had to be done with discrete parts because the bipolar-junction semiconductors of the time were just too slow. At this time, \u003ca href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MOSFET#History\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eMOSFETs were just becoming manufacturable\u003c/a\u003e, but were even slower still. The MESFET, without its insulating oxide layer between the metal and the silicon, had less capacitance, and switched faster. When silicon feature sizes got small enough that you could do gigahertz work with them, the MESFET was the tech of choice.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAs late as the 1980s, you’d find MESFETs in radio devices. At this time, the feature size of the gates and the thickness of the oxide layer in MOSFETs kept them out of the game. But as CPU manufacturers pushed CMOS theses features smaller, not only did we get chips like the 8086 and 80386, \u003ca href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CHMOS\" target=\"_blank\"\u003etwo of Intel’s earliest CMOS designs\u003c/a\u003e, but the tech started getting fast enough for RF. And the world never looked back.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you’re interested in the history of the modern monolithic RF ICs, definitely give the 18-minute video a watch. (You can \u003ca href=\"https://youtu.be/b2g23mWskmw?t=214\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eskip the first three or so\u003c/a\u003e if you’re already a radio head.) If you just want to build some radio circuits, \u003ca href=\"https://hackaday.com/2016/03/23/michael-ossmann-makes-you-an-rf-design-hero/\"\u003ethis fantastic talk from [Michael Ossmann] at the first-ever Supercon\u003c/a\u003e will make you an RF design hero. His secrets? Among them, making the most of exactly these modern everything-in-one-chip RF ICs so that you don’t have to think about that side of things too hard.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThanks [Stephen] for the tip!\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"How Moore’s Law Revolutionized RF-CMOS\" width=\"800\" height=\"450\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/b2g23mWskmw?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen=\"\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\t            \u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003cul\u003e\n    \t\t\t\t\t\u003cli\u003e\n    \t\t\t\t\u003ca href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fhackaday.com%2F2025%2F04%2F05%2Fhow-shrinking-feature-size-made-modern-wireless-work%2F\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\n    \t\t\t\t\t\u003ci\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://hackaday.com/wp-content/themes/hackaday-2/img/share_face.png\"/\u003e \u003c/i\u003e\n    \t\t\t\t\t\t